\i0\b\fs24 \cf0 My garden is near the house so it is convenient for tending and picking. 
\b0 \

\b Raised beds:
\b0  We have a high water table, so I had to build raised beds. Beds are 4\'92 wide x 10\'92 long with space between to walk and move a wheelbarrow. The boards are 2\'94 thick, 10\'94 high rough-sawn hemlock from a local sawmill. Wood chips between beds provided a dry, clean and weed free space.\

\b Soil preparation:
\b0  The soil was heavy clay and I did not see any earthworms. There was no extra soil to fill the raised beds, so I bought topsoil. This soil needed organic matter, lime, and rock powders for trace minerals. In the past, to make compost, I had sources of cow manure and leaves, but starting again I had to find new sources. Raising animals (sheep, chickens and geese) was a source for manure and bedding materials (hay and straw.) Garden excess and weeds were fed to the animals, and other plant material went on the compost pile. \

\b Double digging:
\b0  To get a faster start creating more organic matter in my soil, I double dig the beds, making a foot wide trench across the width of the bed, filling it with material to decompose (leaves, animal manure and bedding, etc.). Then making another trench beside it, putting the soil from the new trench on top of the compostable material just placed in the previous trench.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri-1440\sl288\slmult1\sa40\ql\qnatural

\b \cf0 Corner brackets
\b0  for raised beds are sold, but are expensive. \
My first raised beds were fastened with 6\'94 long screws. A corded drill with hex bit was needed for the power to drive in the screws.\
On the internet, I saw the use of Simpson Strong-Tie Plates, which can be easily bent to a 90\'b0 angle and then fastened with smaller screws using a battery screw gun. I now use these plates. Support stakes on the bed sides are now not necessary.\
