\b \cf0 Starting plants inside 
\b0 gives you a head start on spring. In Maine, our spring is cold because of the effect of the ocean, so getting an early start makes a big difference.\
Shelves can be made to hold several light fixtures for growing lights.\
Originally, I simply started with lights under a table, a chain going over the table to hold the lights up and the plants on the floor. The chain was adjustable to change the height as the plants grow.\
Garden centers sell timers, so you can set the times you want the lights on and off.\
The area should be warm, 65\'b0+ so the seeds will germinate and plants grow. I use a small room with a south window. If the temperature is too cool I use a small heater to make it warmer.\
The top shelf has two cell trays of onions, the first plants I start. The second shelf has kale in 6-pack trays and 3\'94 pots with short edible podded peas.\
The bottom shelf has bowls of sprouting grains for the chickens and geese.\
